	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Pacific trade policy: Fiji reverts to bilateral non-reciprocal approach</h1>

			
			<h4>
												25 December 2010
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>In a speech on 29 November 2010 at the Fiji Australia New Zealand Business Forum, the Fijian Permanent Secretary of Foreign Affairs and International Cooperation, Mr Solo Mara, argued that ‘Fiji does not want to be part of a regional trade arrangement where it is treated as a subordinate by its neighbours.’ The statement arose from Fiji’s ongoing suspension from the Pacific Islands Forum (PIF) for the takeover of a democratically elected government in 2006 by the Fijian military. The PIF Leaders, without Fiji, had agreed to start the negotiations on a new free-trade agreement (FTA), referred to as PACER Plus, with Fiji due to be informed of the progress only after the end of each negotiation session by the Chief Trade Adviser for the Pacific Island Countries that are negotiating with Australia and New Zealand.</p><p>In response to the PIF Leaders’ decision, Fiji invoked the relevant provisions of the PACER Agreement and suspended Part Two of the agreement, effectively absolving itself from any legally binding obligations of any concluded PACER Plus agreement.</p><p>The Permanent Secretary suggested that instead of participating in PACER Plus, Fiji would resort to the preferential and non-reciprocal provisions of the South Pacific Regional Trade and Economic Cooperation Agreement (SPARTECA) for its trade with Australia and New Zealand, or the bilateral economic framework agreement with Australia – the Fiji-Australia Trade and Economic Relations Agreement (FATERA) – for its specific trade with Australia. He was upbeat, however, about Fiji’s trade surplus situation when it comes to trading in services – due essentially to the strength of Fiji’s tourism industry. In this context, Permanent Secretary Mara proposed strengthening the provisions of FATERA in this area. For Fiji’s trade with New Zealand, Mr Mara stated that Fiji wishes to explore a bilateral trade agreement.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>
Fiji Times/PACNEWS, ‘Fiji wants fair trade’, 29 November 2010<br/>
<a href="http://www.pina.com.fj/index.php?p=pacnews&amp;m=read&amp;o=5870903514cf2bc6d38cd8428c2363" target="_self">http://www.pina.com.fj/index.php?p=pacnews&amp;m=read&amp;o=5870903514cf...</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>Fiji’s suspension of Part Two of the PACER agreement, effectively ruling itself out of the PACER Plus negotiations, is seen by analysts as a retrograde step in the Pacific’s regional economic integration efforts. The preference for reverting to a 30-year-old preferential and non-reciprocal trade agreement and bilateral trade agreements appears out of step with the trends in the multilateral trading system, which is increasingly being built on reciprocal trade liberalisation and removal of trade protectionism. It also neglects the failure of such non-reciprocal arrangements to promote trade in goods (for example, since 2000, Fiji’s exports of textile, clothing and footwear products have declined). It also neglects the irrelevance of this bilateral non-reciprocal framework to the important trends in trade in services which are under way. Furthermore, the desire to further elaborate these traditional non-reciprocal preferential trade arrangements leaves unaddressed the question of how this is to be achieved, given the serious strains in political relations arising from the 2006 military coup. The move does however reflect a recent global trend towards more protectionist trading mechanisms and trade and trade-related policy instruments.</p><p>The seed of retrogression depicted above is encroaching on the plurilateral EU-PACPS [Assistance to Pacific ACP States] EPA process. For the Pacific, the prospects of a comprehensive EPA, after Fiji and PNG have initialled and signed their interim EPA (IEPA), seem somewhat remote. The fear of unprecedented trade liberalisation, especially by small island developing states, most of which are also least developed countries (LDCs), seems to be driving them to opt for the unilateral GSP and EBA as their preferred long-term solutions.</p><p>While regional politics is driving Fiji towards taking a retrograde step from an FTA to preferential trading arrangements and trade non-reciprocity, the PACP LDCs on the other hand are beginning to see such retrogression as a solution to their fear of being overwhelmed by free trade – and especially free trade that they do not believe is being moderated by genuine developmental considerations.</p>
		</div>
		
